==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|flēon}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*fleuhaną}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*plewk-}}, {{m|ine-pro|*plew-||to fly, flow, run}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/fliː/|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|iː|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-flee.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{homophones|lang=en|flea}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|flees|fleeing|fled|fled}}

# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[run]] [[away]]; to [[escape]].
#: {{ux|en|The prisoner tried to '''flee''', but was caught by the guards.}}
#* {{quote-book|year=1922|author={{w|Michael Arlen}}|title=[http://openlibrary.org/works/OL1519647W “Piracy”: A Romantic Chronicle of These Days]|chapter=Ep./4/2
|passage=As they turned into Hertford Street they startled a robin from the poet's head on a barren fountain, and he '''fled''' away with a cameo note.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[escape]] from.
#: {{ux|en|Many people '''fled''' the country as war [[loomed]].}}
#: {{ux|en|Thousands of people moved northward trying to '''flee''' the [[drought]].}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[disappear]] [[quickly]]; to [[vanish]].
#: {{ux|en|Ethereal products '''flee''' once freely exposed to air.}}

